    "body": "Le 13 janv. 2013 à 14:14, Honghe a écrit :\n\n> @Carreau and something interesting.\n> If apply \"%edit -x test.py\" to open test.py file with Sublime, and Sublime has not been opened, this command will block IPthon.\n> If open Sublime before apply \"%edit -x test.py\", then will not block IPython.\n\n%edit just do \n- Create a file with content\n- sublime [the file]\n- read the file \n- execute it. \n\nif sublime is already launched,\n- sublime [the file]\n  will not block, but this is the case for sublime not all editors. \n\nso this is not really surprising. \n\n> Yes, I want to know the mechanism of IPython talks with editor.\n\nIf you want to talk to an IPython kernel, you can read the docs about the protocol. \nhttp://ipython.org/ipython-doc/dev/development/messaging.html\n\nOr look at the vim example :\nhttps://github.com/ivanov/vim-ipython\n"
  },
